# Singleton Design Pattern with Serialization:
    Imagine you're running a movie ticket counter. You have only one control desk where bookings are managed.
    Everyone — customers, staff, and online systems — must use this one desk to book seats. Why? Because
    if multiple desks are used, two people might book the same seat at the same time. Total chaos! 😩

    That’s why you decided to follow a rule: only one control desk exists — no matter what.

    This is exactly what the Singleton Design Pattern does in Java. It makes sure only one object of a class
    is created and used across your entire program. Sounds perfect, right?

    But now, imagine you save this control desk’s data to a file (using something called serialization) and
    later load it back (deserialization). Here's the twist — instead of bringing back your original desk,
    Java creates a brand-new one! 😲 Oops! That breaks our rule of “only one.”

Q1. What is the Singleton Pattern?
    The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one object (instance)
    and gives you a way to access it globally from anywhere in your program.

    When a Singleton is serialized and then deserialized, Java actually creates a new object,
    breaking the Singleton pattern. Now, instead of one control panel, you have two — and that ruins everything.

    # Why It Matters:
        If your Singleton class is used in core logic (like settings, configuration, logging), you can’t afford
        to have two different versions of it. So if you ever save and load a Singleton, you must protect it from duplication.